    "title": "Bangladesh\u2019s net equity inflows, which is the measure for new foreign direct inv...",
    "description": "Bangladesh\u2019s net equity inflows, which is the measure for new foreign direct investment, barely saw any growth in 2025; it stood at $554.63 million, which is a growth of 1.8% from 2024, the year that saw the most intense political upheaval in two decades. Even more troubling is the collapse in the investment pipeline. According to the Economic Review 2025, registered private investment projects dropped by 58% year-on-year. This forward-looking indicator suggested that the cautious \u201cwait-and-see\u201d approach of 2024 had hardened into a decisive \u201cgo elsewhere\u201d stance by 2025, says The Daily Star. I will now share an example that will further explain the pathetic state of FDI in the 18 months Ashik Chowdhury has been the BIDA chair. In December last year, the key decision-maker of a foreign Roll-Up Fund had a meeting with Ashik about possible investment in Bangladesh. When asked why one should invest in Bangladesh, Ashik told the person, a commercially driven investor, that if they invest, Bangladesh will see more employment and our reserve will grow. That investor\u2019s reaction later was, \"Am I here for charity?\u201d Ashik spouted his lines reserved for development finance institutions \u2014 shambolic for someone who bills himself as a top foreign banker who has given up his life of luxury abroad to serve Bangladesh. The investor then asked Ashik that since Bangladesh's credit rating is low, can they borrow at his holding company level and funnel it to the Bangladeshi operating company that the fund intends to invest in. Ashik replied it's not possible, when BIDA itself approved such loans in the last one year, one most recently for RAK. I mean, Bangladesh Bank reports on intracompany loans in its FDI reporting. Such is his know-how on things for which he was put in that chair. For all his posturing of modernising the BIDA and BEZA, he has not updated the 30-year-old investor protection laws, which should have been his first job when he got into the office. Instead of focusing on real issues, he put all his energy and national resources into going viral in TikTok and Facebook Reels. So it\u2019s very frustrating and infuriating to see such a class-A imposter continue to occupy that seat when all qualified Yunus appointees were let go. I\u2019d urge Prime Minister Tarique Rahman to not fall for all the window-dressing of Ashik by that Bangladesh Nationalist Party-BNP standing committee member \u2014 he will grind that investment flow to a halt. And at this moment, what Bangladesh needs most is investment, for job creation, for jump starting the economy after years of fits and starts.",
    "link": "https://www.facebook.com/saerzulkarnain/posts/pfbid0HvgF8deKK5vWnBPwnCLfmrVM5j2JRcD2cem64qVu6Q1gQ35Ch4Dos86jsVj8Vgyvl",
    "guid": "https://www.facebook.com/saerzulkarnain/posts/pfbid0HvgF8deKK5vWnBPwnCLfmrVM5j2JRcD2cem64qVu6Q1gQ35Ch4Dos86jsVj8Vgyvl",
